		<header>
			
			<h1>High maize prices pose challenges for the East African poultry sector</h1>

			
			<h4>
												12 November 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In Kenya ‘poultry farmers countrywide are scaling back chicken production’ as a result of the ‘soaring costs of feed’, principally maize. Maize supplies have long been a problem in the East African poultry sector, given the competition with consumption needs. The current difficulties are linked to food scarcity and the major famine, which is affecting 12 million people in the wider Eastern African region. This has prompted a search for alternative poultry feed that is cheaper, more nutritious and which does not compete with human consumption needs.</p><p>At the local level, farmers are using traditional crops such as amaranth, millet and sorghum as chicken feed, which can reduce feed costs by up to 40%. Research into other sources of poultry feed has found ‘bulrush millet to be a good replacement for maize due to its higher protein content’ and has ‘also found raw pigeon peas were a suitable source of protein at levels up to 15% in chicken feed rations’.</p><p>High feed prices are also ‘forcing some farmers out of business’ in the neighbouring Ugandan poultry sector, with feed prices more than tripling between February and August 2011, according to industry sources. While the famine in the wider region was a key factor in increased feed costs, difficulties in the supply of local fishmeal have compounded the problem in Uganda. The input price squeeze has been further compounded by the price sensitivity of eggs and poultry meat on the Ugandan market, with any price increases immediately being felt in the form of reduced demand.</p><p>In Uganda, pilot projects introducing new chicken varieties could potentially ease the vulnerability of small-scale poultry producers to rising maize prices. A pilot programme is under way to introduce a new breed of Indian chicken, the Kuroiler. This is a hybrid chicken that is reportedly ‘well suited to resource poor village environments’. The breed has been genetically selected to provide both increased meat and egg output in village conditions (i.e. feeding on agricultural and household waste, with no additional feed costs incurred). In field trials, Kuroilers produced 133% more meat and 462% more eggs. These yield improvements resulted in ‘a 341% increase in income for rural poultry farmers’. This needs to be seen in a context where some 86% of Ugandan poultry stock is being raised in village flocks.</p><p>The importance of getting to grips with feed supply issues is highlighted by developments in Zambia. In Zambia the poultry sector is booming, and production is expected to grow 25% in 2011, following a 15% expansion in 2010 – a rapid recovery after 2009’s 40% downsizing in the poultry sector. However there remains considerable under-utilised capacity within the sector, providing good prospects for further growth.</p><p>This rapid growth is attributed to ‘the reduction in the costs of feed stock and readily available soya and maize on the market’. Currently, 65% of Zambian poultry production is in the flocks of small-scale farmers.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
