<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201108241325.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201108241325.html</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Getting to grips with maintaining access to low-cost poultry feed can be seen as a critical issue in the poultry sector in East Africa. Research into low-cost feed that is not competitive with human consumption needs offers an important means of insulating the poultry sector from the market consequences of the periodic droughts to which the region is vulnerable. Equally, improvements in stock breeds, particularly the introduction of breeds better suited to village-level poultry production systems, potentially offers an important means of stabilising feed costs within that component of the poultry sector that has the greatest impact on village-level food security.</p><p>Potentially, technical improvements to the poultry breeding stock can make an important contribution to household food security in ACP countries, given the importance of village-level production in many ACP poultry sectors. However, if income gains from improved breeding stock are to be sustained, then issues related to the commercialisation of village-level poultry production will need to be addressed alongside any programmes to supply improved breeding stock.</p><p>As the experience in Namibia illustrates, promoting vertically integrated poultry production provides an alternative model for the development of the poultry sector (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Poultry/Poultry-Focus/New-Namibian-poultry-investment-aims-at-self-sufficiency" target="_blank">New Namibian poultry investment aims at self-sufficiency</a>’, November 2011). However, the food security gains are likely to be far less dramatic under this model of poultry sector development, due to the small-scale nature of the changes.</p>
		</div>
		
